
This directory is intended for project header files.

A header file is a file containing C declarations and macro definitions
to be shared between several project source files. You request the use of a
header file in your project source file (C, C++, etc) located in `src` folder
by including it, with the C preprocessing directive `#include'.

```src/main.c

#include "header.h"

int main (void)
{
 ...
}
```

Including a header file produces the same results as copying the header file
into each source file that needs it. Such copying would be time-consuming
and error-prone. With a header file, the related declarations appear
in only one place. If they need to be changed, they can be changed in one
place, and programs that include the header file will automatically use the
new version when next recompiled. The header file eliminates the labor of
finding and changing all the copies as well as the risk that a failure to
find one copy will result in inconsistencies within a program.

In C, the convention is to give header files names that end with `.h'.

Read more about using header files in official GCC documentation:

* Include Syntax
* Include Operation
* Once-Only Headers
* Computed Includes

https://gcc.gnu.org/onlinedocs/cpp/Header-Files.html

---

PickupWinder notes
==================

Final winding position (`endPos`)
---------------------------------

The winding recipe can optionally force the carriage to finish on a chosen
bound:

- `none`: normal behavior, no forced final position
- `high`: finish on the high bound
- `low`: finish on the low bound

`endPosTurns` defines how many final turns must be done while the carriage is
already resting on that bound in order to lock the wire in place.

Predictive final traverse logic
-------------------------------

The final positioning is not done by abruptly sending the carriage to the bound.
Instead, the firmware tries to predict the remaining traverse motion and slow the
current/next pass so that the carriage reaches the requested bound exactly when
the final hold turns begin.

High-level behavior:

1. The firmware computes how much traverse path remains before the requested
	bound (`pathUnits`, expressed in fractions of a pass).
2. It converts that path into nominal turns to reach the bound using the current
	`turnsPerPass`.
3. It compares that with the number of turns remaining before the hold zone.
4. It adjusts the lateral `speedScale` so the carriage arrives on the bound at
	the right moment.
5. Once the bound is reached, lateral motion is stopped and must not restart.

This is intentionally based on remaining turns and traverse geometry, so it can
keep adapting while the winding speed changes during the end of the job.
